Clustering NBA Teams

Yo

October 9, 2018

Question one may ask themselves - how could we come up with a stylistic grouping of NBA teams according to their performances in various statistical categories? How to determine clusters of similar teams?

E.g. one may claim from domain knowledge that San Antonio Spurs and Boston Celtics are pretty similar from many standpoints - solid system provided by tenured head coaches, great perimeter defense, average offense. How do we represent that from modeling/statistical standpoint?

First of all, one has to represent teams as mathematical objects. How though?

Just check a classical Team Per Game Stats table at https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_2018.html. Each team may be represented as a vector of numbers - x \(= (FG, FGA, FG\%, .., PTS) = (x_1,x_2,x_3, ..., x_p) \in R^p\) etc. The number \(p\) of statistical categories determines the length of that vector.

In NBA we got 30 teams, so we can get 30 vectors - x\(_1\), x\(_2\),,x\(_{30}\), each one representing the corresponding team \(i, i=1,\dots,30\), as a mathematical object.

Now the questions of

  • how similar are teams A & B, and
  • how can we group NBA teams stylistically

are translated into

  • how close are are vectors \(x_A\) and \(x_B\), and
  • how can we numerically group/cluster vectors corresponding to NBA teams

Below we will proceed to

  • Scrape the required data on NBA teams by the mid-season of 2017/18.
  • Figure out the statistical categories worth retaining in order to describe an NBA teams.
  • Apply a couple of clustering approaches to group NBA teams.

We need to refer to our \(find\_extra\_table()\) function (details in previous meetup files) to dig out the rest of the tables from that page:

find_extra_table <- function(url_link){
  # Additional tables are within the comment tags -  between "<!--"  and  "-->"
  # Which is why your xpath is missing them.
  
  # Find all the commented nodes. 
  # xml_find_all looks in-between the <> of the object resulting from read_html().
  alt_tables <- xml_find_all(read_html(url_link),"//comment()")
  
  #Among commented nodes, find those containing '<table' reg. expression 
  #raw_parts <- as.character(alt_tables[grep("\\</?table", as.character(alt_tables))])
  raw_parts <- as.character(alt_tables[grep("<table", as.character(alt_tables))])
  
  # Remove the comment begin ("<!--") and end ("-->") tags
  strip_html <- stringi::stri_replace_all_regex(raw_parts, c("<\\!--","-->"),c("",""),
                                                vectorize_all = FALSE)
  
  # Read all the tables that used to be commented before.
  alt_tables <- lapply(grep("<table", strip_html, value = TRUE), function(i){
    rvest::html_table(xml_find_all(read_html(i), "//table"))[[1]]
  })
  
  return(alt_tables)
}

Below we apply \(find\_extra\_table()\) function to our \(url\_link\), and save the teams and opponents stats into appropriately named objects:

Wrangling, Transforming Data into Needed Format.

Next, we need to obtain per-game averages in such categories as FG made, attempted (FGM/A), 3PTM/A, FTM/A, offensive rebounds (ORB), DRB, TRB, AST, STL, BLK, TOV, PF, PTS.

All but the %-type of stats (FG%, 3PT% etc). We can obtain indices of those %-stats and other unwanted columns (team names) as follows (again some data wrangling/string operations):

ind.exclude <- which(grepl("%",names(team_stats)))
ind.exclude <- c(ind.exclude, which(grepl("[a-z]",names(team_stats))))
ind.exclude
## [1]  6  9 12 15  1

Then we only modify these stats, via dividing them by the games played (\(G\) column):

team_stats[,-ind.exclude] <- apply(team_stats[,-ind.exclude],
                                      2,
                                      function(x) x/team_stats$G)

opp_stats[,-ind.exclude] <- apply(opp_stats[,-ind.exclude],
                                      2,
                                      function(x) x/opp_stats$G)

team_stats$G <- opp_stats$G <- NULL

Feature/variable selection.

Now that we got a long list of stats for each team, wed like to narrow that list down for the following reasons:

  • We only have \(n=30\) teams, and in order to have meaningful clustering, we would want number of variables \(p\) to be considerably \(<n\). Otherwise we get into many computational/theoretical issues.
  • We wouldnt want to have heavily correlated features.
  • We need to watch out for collinearity (e.g.FG = 3P + 2P, FGA = 3PA + 2PA, etc)

First, lets check the fancy correlation matrix (see details in previous meetup materials) for the teams own stats:

library(plotrix)

abs.cor <- abs(cor(team_stats[,-1]))
abs.thresh.cor <- ifelse(abs.cor >= 0.8, abs.cor, 0)
                      
color2D.matplot(abs.thresh.cor,
                cs1=c(1,0),cs2=c(1,0),cs3=c(1,0),
                show.legend=T,
                xlab='',
                ylab='',
                axes=F)

par(las=2)
axis(1,at=c(1:ncol(abs.thresh.cor))-0.5,labels=colnames(abs.thresh.cor))
par(las=1)
axis(2,at=c(ncol(abs.thresh.cor):1)-0.5,labels=colnames(abs.thresh.cor))

Lets dispose of certain correlated variables (leaving only one from a correlated group) taking into account our final goal - select features that describe the team stylistically, so that they could be interpreted as a team quality concept:

  • \(FG\) and \(FG\%\) are correlated - Id leave in just \(FG\%\), because we can easily associate it with the concept of team shooting efficiency; Plus \(FGA\) - corresponding to the concept of pace (maybe?) - will pick up the slack on explaining how many shots did the team actually take to produce this efficiency.
  • \(3PA\) correlates with \(3P\) - Id leave in \(3PA\), shows tendency/willingness to shoot threes, while \(3P\%\) will take care of efficiency
  • Id fully dispose of \(2P\) shooting, as itd be collinear for total FG and 3P, while also heavily negatively correlated with \(3P\).
  • Id dispose of \(FT\)/\(FTA\). Cant waste space on that But again - I might be wrong.
  • From the \(ORB\)/\(DRB\)/\(TRB\) triple, which is collinear (\(TRB = ORB + DRB\)), Id leave in \(TRB\) (overall rebounding prowess) and \(ORB\) (activity on offensive boards).
  • \(AST, BLK, Fouls(PF), TOV\) are all good as stand-alone stats and good for describing a team (ball-sharing offense, rim-protecting defense, physical defense, careless offense, respectively)
  • Id get rid of \(STL\) because I will use \(TOV\) from the \(opponent\) table to take care of all things forced turnovers.
  • Should I get rid of points? It feels weird to me to use points as a way to describe teams style, especially when I already have pace, efficiency and all that..
### Var "selection": gotta really minimize the selection, as we just got 30 teams.
needed.vars.team <- c("FGA","FG%","3PA","3P%", "ORB", "TRB", "AST", "BLK", "TOV","PF")

Clustering.

Now that weve settled on the feature vectors that describe each team, we can proceed to clustering.

Scaling.

Prior to applying any clustering methods, first and foremost one should scale the data. Clustering is a very geometrical method, which heavily depends on distances between vectors.

It is very sensitive to the variable scales, and can be easily dominated by variables that have higher standard deviations (due to units of measurement, for example).

Just as a toy example, presume you have a Team A that takes 83 FGA and shoots 0.40 from the field, while

  • Team B has 83 FGA and shoots 0.30 from the field.
  • Team C has 84 FGA and shoots 0.40 from the field.

Which team (B or C) is more similar to A?

From logical perspective, difference of 1 FG attempt is nothing compared to 0.1 in field goal percentage, and wed consider team C to be closer to A.

But from clustering algorithms perspective, 1 is always greater than 0.1, and it will claim that Team B is closer stylistically to Team A, which is something that can be avoided by scaling.

Scaling a variable X means dividing it by its STANDARD DEVIATION. For example, scaling \(FGA\) variable means substituting it for \(FGA/sd(FGA)\). Scaling the whole data set? You simply scale each variable (<-> column) of the data set (e.g. \(FGA\) for \(FGA/sd(FGA)\), \(FG\%\) for \(FG\%/sd(FG\%)\), etc).

That way we obtain the same measure units for each variable. Now they are all measured in standard deviations (1 unit = 1 standard deviation). What did we have before scaling? We had \(FG\%\) measured in percentages, \(FGA\) in attempts (different units).

For a toy example, lets look at \((FGA, FG\%)\) pair of variables, and check out three teams: \(Wizards\), \(Warriors\), \(76ers\). In particular, well see how close are \(Wizards\) to the other two teams.

Before scaling: \(Wizards\) are considered to be closer to GSW in shooting from the field than they are to Philly.

all_stats[c(30,10,23),c("FGA.x","FG%.x")]       # FGA, FG% values for 3 teams
##                          FGA.x FG%.x
## Washington Wizards    85.73333 0.465
## Golden State Warriors 85.54348 0.509
## Philadelphia 76ers    86.80000 0.462
dist(all_stats[c(30,10,23),c("FGA.x","FG%.x")]) # Eucledian distances between 3 teams
##                       Washington Wizards Golden State Warriors
## Golden State Warriors           0.194887                      
## Philadelphia 76ers              1.066671              1.257400

After scaling: Were back to normal. \(Wizards\) are closer to \(Philly\) than to \(GSW\).

all_stats.scaled <- scale(all_stats) # Scaling (dividing each) # Scaling (dividing each variable by its st. dev.)

Hierarchical clustering.

See a nice video on hierarchical clustering (especially the parts from 0:00 to 6:30, and from 9:50 to 12:50):

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rg2cjfMsCk4.

An agglomerative hierarchical clustering approach will go as follows:

  • Initially, each object is assigned to its own cluster,
  • At each iteration the algorithm joins (agglomerates) two most similar clusters
  • Until all objects got lumped into one huge final cluster.

To project onto our case:

  • We start with 30 clusters, each has just one team,
  • Then we merge two most similar teams (=> get 29 clusters),
  • Then we mergo two most similar clusters from those 29 (=> get 28 clusters),
  • etc until we get that single full cluster.

Then, in order to look for meaningful results, one has to check the middle iterations of hierarchical approach, before it all gets lumped.

Function \(hclust()\) performs hierarchical clustering in \(R\). As an argument it needs a distance matrix - matrix of distances between your objects (in our case - team vectors) - which it uses to evaluate cluster similarity. Below we will calculate the distance matrix and perform an agglomerative hierarchical clustering with complete linkage (other options include average, single etc)

# Distance matrix
team.dist <- dist(all_stats)
# team.dist

# Hierarchical clustering algorithm.
team.hc <- hclust(team.dist, method = "complete")

# Plot the resulted hierarchy of clusters.
plot(team.hc,
     hang = -1)

Unfortunately, its not the most convenient plot to read. Lets flip it over a bit, and color it up via \(dendextend\) library (thanks to Jared) to provide the following dendrogram:

# Function to calculate ranks of teams with respect to a stat.

ranking.calc <- function(stat,team){
  sapply(team, function(x) which(x == names(sort(all_stats[,stat],decreasing = T))))
}

Partitioning Methods: K-Means Clustering.

As an alternative to hierarchical clustering, there are partitioning methods. The most popular of those is called \(K\)-means. \(K\)-means is much better for bigger datasets, where computational demands become an issue (not precisely our case, but still good to know).

A great video on \(K\)-means clustering (especially first 9 minutes):

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RD0nNK51Fp8

In the end,

  • Algorithm yields \(K\) centroids - average vectors, which serve as centers of their respective clusters.
  • Each object in the data is assigned to the cluster with the closest centroid.

Function \(kmeans()\) in \(R\) allows us to run the \(K\)-means clustering:

kmeans(all_stats, centers=5, nstart=50,iter.max = 100)

Natural questions - how do we select \(K\)? One approach is as follows:

  • Run \(K\)-means for a grid of \(K\) values (from \(1\) up to \(n-1\)).
  • Record the within-cluster sum of squares (WSS) metric for each \(K\) value, which shows how homogeneous (hence good) your clusters are
  • Provide the elbow plot of those WSS values as \(K\) increases, look for the elbow point - the point thats most removed from the straight line connecting first and last WSS values - which will correspond to an optimal" \(K\) value.
k.max <- 29
wss <- sapply(1:k.max, 
              function(k){kmeans(all_stats, k, nstart=50,iter.max = 100)$tot.withinss})
wss
##  [1] 522.000000 435.561696 373.943671 319.765168 276.714902 247.321835
##  [7] 221.284706 199.865235 179.620996 160.005531 145.700966 131.821546
## [13] 120.340610 110.139097 100.092782  91.284257  81.341209  73.657254
## [19]  65.947188  58.439662  51.239390  44.629691  36.527854  29.719352
## [25]  23.610531  17.687266  12.541165   7.412245   2.970482
plot(1:k.max, wss,
     type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
     xlab="Number of clusters K",
     ylab="Total within-clusters sum of squares")

lines(c(1,k.max),c(wss[1],wss[k.max]))

\(K=6,7\) look pretty close to having the longest perpendicular distance to the straight line, lets go with \(K=7\).
